---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import '../../../styles/pages/creations.css';

const latestDesigns = [
  {
    title: 'Quick Door Hangers in Bambu Studio',
    category: 'Beginner design',
    material: 'PLA',
    designTime: 'About 10–15 minutes',
    videoUrl: 'https://youtube.com/shorts/N8sHC7B3SuU?feature=share',
    etsyUrl:
      'https://www.etsy.com/listing/4498146938/3d-printed-door-handle-tag-custom-text',
    description:
      'A quick custom door hanger made in Bambu Studio using basic shapes, a negative cylinder cutout, and raised decorative parts.',
    uses: [
      'Pet room signs',
      'Office doors',
      'Maker spaces',
      'Seasonal hangers',
    ],
    body: [
      'This was a quick 3D printed door hanger project made directly in Bambu Studio. The idea was simple: start with a basic shape, cut out the door handle opening, add a raised design, and print something useful without needing to jump into full CAD software.',
      'The hanger body was made from a cube sized at 80 × 170 × 5mm. I used 5mm thickness for the video because I was also recording a time-lapse on the X1C and wanted the print to have a bit more presence. For regular use, you could probably get away with 3mm thick and save some print time and filament.',
      'The door handle opening was made with a negative cylinder sized at 53 × 53 × 20mm. I usually leave negative parts unmerged while I am prototyping because the slicer removes them during slicing anyway. For a final polished file, merging things properly is probably the cleaner route.',
      'After the base shape was set, I selected the main cube, added a part, and loaded in a paw print .3mf file. Adding it as part of the main object makes it easy to position the paw print on the hanger while keeping it raised from the surface.',
      'Once the layout was done, it was just a quick slice and print. That is the nice thing about this kind of project: once the basic shape works, you can make all kinds of versions with text, flags, pet themes, office signs, holiday designs, or whatever else you feel like messing with.',
      'This is a good beginner-friendly print because it shows how much you can do with basic shapes and a little experimentation. Nothing fancy, no overthinking, just plastic doing something useful. Imagine that.',
    ],
    images: [
      {
        src: '/images/creations/3d-printing/door-hangers/door-hangers-bambu-studio.png',
        alt: 'Several custom 3D printed door hanger designs laid out in Bambu Studio',
        caption: 'A few quick door hanger variations laid out in Bambu Studio.',
      },
      {
        src: '/images/creations/3d-printing/door-hangers/paw-print-door-hanger.JPG',
        alt: 'Black 3D printed door hanger with a raised brown paw print hanging on a door knob',
        caption: 'The finished paw print hanger doing its job on the door.',
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    title: '3D Printed Bag Clips',
    category: 'Useful print',
    material: 'PLA',
    designTime: 'About 20 minutes',
    etsyUrl:
      'https://www.etsy.com/listing/4505801454/reusable-sliding-bag-clips-3d-printed?variation0=6617469000',
    description:
      'A quick utility print designed after my workshop clamps kept being borrowed for keeping bags closed.',
    uses: ['Coffee bags', 'Dog treats', 'Chips', 'Frozen foods'],
    body: [
      'This was one of those small workshop wins that started with a simple problem: people kept stealing my clamps to keep bags closed.',
      'Coffee bags, dog treats, chips, frozen food, tortilla chips — somehow they all needed a clip, and somehow my regular clamps kept vanishing into the kitchen. So instead of sacrificing more workshop gear to the snack cupboard, I designed a dedicated set of 3D printed bag clips.',
      'The design took about 20 minutes and is printed in PLA. The shape is intentionally simple: wide enough to grip a folded bag, curved enough to make it easy to grab, and chunky enough that it does not feel flimsy in daily use.',
      'These are not complicated prints, and that is the whole point. They solve a real problem, print quickly, and are useful immediately.',
    ],
    images: [
      {
        src: '/images/creations/3d-printing/bag-clips/bag-clip-white.JPG',
        alt: 'White 3D printed bag clip holding a tortilla chip bag closed',
        caption: 'A white PLA bag clip doing exactly what it was made for.',
      },
      {
        src: '/images/creations/3d-printing/bag-clips/bag-clip-green.JPG',
        alt: 'Green 3D printed bag clip holding a tortilla chip bag closed',
        caption:
          'Same design, different color, still saving my actual clamps from snack duty.',
      },
      {
        src: '/images/creations/3d-printing/bag-clips/bag-clip-set.JPG',
        alt: 'Set of colorful 3D printed bag clips standing in a holder',
        caption: 'A small batch of PLA clips with a simple storage base.',
      },
    ],
  },
];

const olderDesigns = [
  {
    title: 'Older Designs Coming Soon',
    category: 'Archive',
    description:
      'Older 3D printed creations will live here once the latest section starts filling up.',
    href: '#',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title='3D Printing | Eddie Saunders'
  description='Created and 3D printed products, market pieces, Etsy items, and custom creations.'
>
  <section class='page-hero creations-hero'>
    <p class='eyebrow'>Creations</p>
    <h1>3D Printing</h1>
    <p>
      Useful prints, practical experiments, prototypes, and the occasional bit
      of plastic nonsense.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class='creations-feature-section'>
    <div class='creations-feature-copy'>
      <p class='eyebrow'>Design / Print / Test</p>
      <h2>
        Useful prints, practical experiments, and the occasional plastic
        nonsense
      </h2>

      <p>
        3D printing is one of my favorite ways to turn a rough idea into
        something real without waiting six months, ordering weird parts, or
        pretending the first version will be perfect.
      </p>

      <p>
        Most of what I make starts as a practical problem: a bracket, a holder,
        a jig, a shop helper, a small replacement part, or an idea that needs to
        exist in the real world before I can decide whether it is useful or
        ridiculous. Sometimes it is both. That is part of the fun.
      </p>

      <p>
        This page collects my 3D printing notes, experiments, useful prints,
        failed attempts, design lessons, and finished creations. Some projects
        are functional, some are decorative, and some are just me seeing what
        happens when plastic, patience, and stubbornness are put in the same
        room.
      </p>

      <p>
        The goal is simple: design useful things, print them, test them, improve
        them, and share what I learned along the way.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section
    class='creations-latest-section'
    aria-labelledby='latest-prints-heading'
  >
    <div class='section-content'>
      <div class='section-header'>
        <p class='eyebrow'>Latest</p>
        <h2 id='latest-prints-heading'>Latest 3D Printed Designs</h2>
        <p>
          Fresh prints, current prototypes, and useful designs as they are
          documented.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class='print-design-list'>
        {
          latestDesigns.map((design) => (
            <article class='print-design-card'>
              <div class='print-design-content'>
                <p class='creation-card-category'>{design.category}</p>
                <h3>{design.title}</h3>

                <p class='print-design-summary'>{design.description}</p>

                <div class='print-design-meta' aria-label='Design details'>
                  <span>Material: {design.material}</span>
                  <span>Design time: {design.designTime}</span>
                </div>

                {design.body.map((paragraph) => (
                  <p>{paragraph}</p>
                ))}

                {design.videoUrl && (
                  <a
                    href={design.videoUrl}
                    class='print-video-link'
                    target='_blank'
                    rel='noopener noreferrer'
                  >
                    YouTube Short
                  </a>
                )}

                {design.etsyUrl && (
                  <a
                    href={design.etsyUrl}
                    class='print-video-link'
                    target='_blank'
                    rel='noopener noreferrer'
                  >
                    View Etsy Listing
                  </a>
                )}

                <div class='print-use-list' aria-label='Used for'>
                  {design.uses.map((use) => (
                    <span>{use}</span>
                  ))}
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class='print-design-images'>
                {design.images.map((image) => (
                  <figure class='print-design-image'>
                    <img src={image.src} alt={image.alt} loading='lazy' />
                    <figcaption>{image.caption}</figcaption>
                  </figure>
                ))}
              </div>
            </article>
          ))
        }
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class='creations-archive-section'>
    <div class='section-content'>
      <div class='section-header'>
        <p class='eyebrow'>Archive</p>
        <h2>Older 3D Printed Designs</h2>
        <p>
          As the latest section fills up, older designs will move here so the
          page stays easy to browse.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class='creation-card-grid'>
        {
          olderDesigns.map((design) => (
            <article class='creation-card'>
              <div>
                <p class='creation-card-category'>{design.category}</p>
                <h3>{design.title}</h3>
                <p>{design.description}</p>
              </div>

              {design.href !== '#' && (
                <a href={design.href} class='creation-card-link'>
                  View design
                </a>
              )}
            </article>
          ))
        }
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
